{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RLHE6MxbMMDseK4HdRvqUJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The problem is clear. The ConfigMap `es-config` has `node.name: ` (empty string / null value) which was set by the precondition. The precondition applied a new ConfigMap with a literal `${POD_NAME}` variable that wasn't substituted, leaving `node.name` empty. The other two nodes (es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-1) were already running when the ConfigMap was changed, so they kept their existing `node.name` values in memory. But es-cluster-2 was restarted after the ConfigMap was changed, so it picks up the broken config with `node.name: ` (empty).\nThe precondition applied the elasticsearch configuration with `node.name: ${POD_NAME}` as a literal string instead of having it substituted, which resulted in a blank value that triggers the null-valued setting error. The fix would be to either remove the `node.name` setting entirely so Elasticsearch derives it from the pod hostname, or set it to a proper value.\n\nThe other two pods are still running because they started before the broken ConfigMap was applied and retained their original configuration, but es-cluster-2 was deleted and recreated, forcing it to pick up the new broken ConfigMap. I'm also noticing the `discovery.seed_hosts` is pointing to the wrong service DNS name—it should be `elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` instead of `default.svc.cluster.local`. Let me check what the StatefulSet actually specifies.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1567,"cache_read_input_tokens":31305,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1567},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1f7bc296-4427-4840-a063-28a12f2b