{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GDnvY3b6EUbH4VyUBFgre4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. The original ConfigMap in the StatefulSet has `node.name: ${POD_NAME}` (a variable reference), and the StatefulSet has an env var `POD_NAME` that comes from the pod's metadata.name. However, the `${POD_NAME}` substitution in the `elasticsearch.yml` is NOT done automatically - ES doesn't support environment variable substitution in its config files!\n\n2. Wait, but es-cluster-0 is running with `node.name: ${POD_NAME}` in its config file... and it's showing up as `es-cluster-0` in `/_cat/nodes`. \n\n3. So Elasticsearch actually does support `${ENV_VAR}` substitution in its config files - that's a built-in feature.\n\n4. The precondition script applied a broken ConfigMap with `node.name:` set to empty whitespace instead of `${POD_NAME}`, which causes es-cluster-2 to fail on restart with a null-valued setting error.\n\n5. The `discovery.seed_hosts` in that broken ConfigMap is also pointing to the wrong location instead of using the proper pod DNS names.\n\nThe fix requires updating the ConfigMap back to the correct values - `node.name: ${POD_NAME}` for dynamic substitution and `discovery.seed_hosts` pointing to the actual headless service pod names. Then es-cluster-2 needs to be restarted to pick up the corrected config. I'm wondering whether updating the ConfigMap will affect the already-running pods, since Kubernetes eventually syncs mounted ConfigMap files when they change.\n\nActually, the key detail here is the `subPath` mount in the StatefulSet - when using `subPath`, ConfigMap updates don't propagate to the mounted files automatically like they would without it. So the existing pods will keep their current working configuration even after the ConfigMap is updated. This means I can safely update the ConfigMap and just delete es-cluster-2 to force it to restart with the new config.\n\nThe corrected ConfigMap needs to restore `node.name: ${POD_NAME}` (which Elasticsearch substitutes from the environment variable), fix the seed_hosts to include all three nodes with their proper DNS names, and ensure the initial_master_nodes list matches the actual node names.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2308,"cache_read_input_tokens":32872,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2308},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1f7bc296-4427-4840-a063-28a12f2b3c91","uuid":"0878dad6-6461-48f8-ae43-a38dcb3cab48","request_id":"req_011CcfwkopAff4yb857A3jrB"}
